## **Lecture 1: Introduction to HTML5 & CSS3**

### **1. What is HTML5?**
HTML5 is the latest version of **HyperText Markup Language (HTML)**, used to create structured web pages and web applications. It introduces new elements, attributes, and behaviors to improve web development.

#### **Real-world example:**
- Think of **HTML as the blueprint** of a house. It defines the structure – where walls, rooms, windows, and doors are placed.

### **2. Features of HTML5**
- **New Semantic Elements:** `<header>`, `<nav>`, `<section>`, `<article>`, `<footer>`
- **Multimedia Support:** `<audio>`, `<video>` without external plugins like Flash.
- **Form Enhancements:** `<input type="date">`, `<input type="email">`
- **Canvas & SVG:** 2D and vector graphics for animations.
- **Geolocation API:** Fetch user location in real-time.

#### **Real-world example:**
- A news website uses `<article>` for each news post, `<header>` for the title, and `<footer>` for author details.

### **3. Basic HTML5 Page Structure**

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>My First HTML5 Page</title>
</head>
<body>
    <header>
        <h1>Welcome to HTML5</h1>
    </header>
    <section>
        <p>This is a sample paragraph in HTML5.</p>
    </section>
    <footer>
        <p>© 2025 My Website</p>
    </footer>
</body>
</html>

## **Lecture 1 (Continued): Introduction to CSS3**
### **1. What is CSS3?**
CSS3 (**Cascading Style Sheets 3**) is used to design and style HTML elements. It controls layout, colors, fonts, and animations.

#### **Real-world example:**
- If HTML is a house’s **structure**, CSS is the **paint and decoration**—color, layout, fonts, etc.

### **2. Features of CSS3**
- **Selectors:** Target specific elements (`.class`, `#id`, `element`)
- **Media Queries:** Make websites responsive for different screen sizes.
- **Animations & Transitions:** Create interactive effects.
- **Flexbox & Grid:** Advanced layout systems.

### **3. CSS3 Syntax**

body {
    background-color: lightblue;
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
}

h1 {
    color: darkblue;
    text-align: center;
}

p {
    font-size: 18px;
    line-height: 1.5;
}

### **4. Real-World Example: Styling a Card**
#### **HTML:**

<div class="card">
    <img src="profile.jpg" alt="Profile Picture">
    <h2>John Doe</h2>
    <p>Web Developer</p>
</div>

#### **CSS:**
.card {
    width: 250px;
    border: 2px solid #000;
    padding: 10px;
    text-align: center;
    border-radius: 10px;
    box-shadow: 2px 2px 5px gray;
}
This creates a **beautiful profile card**—just like what we see on social media.

---

## **Conclusion**
- **HTML5 gives structure.**
- **CSS3 makes it look attractive.**
- **Together, they create a modern, user-friendly website.**
